 If `~/.local/bin` is not on `PATH`, put the symlink in a directory that is. Verify with `hive --version`, then run `hive daemon install` once to install and enable the per-user daemon service from that symlink. The dev-clone path skips signed-release verification, but the same daemon installer writes the current systemd-user or launchd template.
 
+### Local web (non-Docker)
+
+From a source checkout, local web is available without the hivebox container:
+
+```bash
+hive setup --json --yes   # preflight, daemon install/enroll, report web command
+hive web                  # foreground Rails server on 127.0.0.1:4567
+hive web install --force  # optional separate hive-web user service
+hive web start
+hive web status --json
+```
+
+`hive setup --service --yes` installs and starts the separate `hive-web` service instead of launching the foreground server. The default bind stays loopback-only (`127.0.0.1:4567`) and needs no auth. A non-loopback bind is refused unless GitHub owner auth is configured or you explicitly pass `--unsafe` / set `web.allow_public_unsafe: true`.
+
+The released `hive-cli` gem still does not package the Rails app. Use a source checkout or set `HIVEBOX_WEB_APP_DIR` to the `web/` app directory; Docker/hivebox remains the packaged browser path.
+
 ### Install via a coding agent
 
 To have Claude Code, Codex, or another agent CLI install Hive for you (with OS detection, channel selection, Apache Hive collision handling, and `hive init` follow-up), paste the prompt at [install.md](install.md) into the agent. It's the canonical source for agent-driven install — keep it pinned in your agent's context if you reinstall often.
