+## Setup And Local Web
+
+`hive setup` is the source-checkout local web provisioner: it runs the local dependency preflight, bootstraps Hive-owned dependencies (`qmd`, the `web/` bundle), records selected agent backends, installs the daemon with the current Hive binary, enrolls the current registered project, and prepares local web. With `--json`, it emits a `hive-setup.v1` envelope with one row per step. By default it launches foreground `hive web`; pass `--service` to install and start the separate `hive-web` user service.
+
+`hive web` without a subcommand remains the foreground Rails server. `hive web run` is the explicit spelling. `hive web install [--force]`, `start`, `stop`, and `status [--json]` manage the local web service and report loopback health through `hive-web-status.v1`. The default bind is `127.0.0.1:4567`; non-loopback binds are refused unless GitHub owner auth is configured or the operator explicitly passes `--unsafe` / sets `web.allow_public_unsafe: true`.
+
+The Rails app is still not packaged inside the `hive-cli` gem. Run local web from a source checkout or set `HIVEBOX_WEB_APP_DIR`; Docker/hivebox remains the packaged browser install.
+
 ## Bot And TUI
 
 `hive tui` opens the terminal dashboard for humans. `hive bot start|stop|status|reload|tail|install` runs the Telegram surface for human-input gates. Both read the same state as the CLI; the TUI intentionally rejects `--json`. `hive bot install [--force] [--json]` installs and enables a per-user autostart service for the bot (systemd-user on Linux, launchd on macOS) so it survives reboot/login — opt-in, mirroring `hive daemon install`; the token comes from `~/.config/hive/.env`, and `hive uninstall` removes the service.
